==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*wintra-'', probably representing a nasalised variant of Indo-European ''*wed-, *aud-'' ‘water’ (English [[water]], [[wet]]).  Cognate with Old Frisian ''winter'', Old Saxon ''winter'' (Dutch [[winter#Dutch|winter]]), Old High German [[wintar]] (German [[Winter]]), Old Norse [[vetr]] (Swedish [[vinter]]), Gothic [[𐍅𐌹𐌽𐍄𐍂𐌿𐍃]]; and, outside the Germanic languages, with Latin [[unda]] ‘wave’, Lithuanian [[vanduo|vanduõ]] ‘water’.

